Sprint Review (4 points)
At the end of the sprint, the team will conduct a sprint review. Show evidence that the team
completed a thorough sprint review. As part of that evidence, each team needs to invite
another team for the review. In your README, answer the following questions:

a. What did you learn from doing our first sprint?
Communication both between team members and with the client are very important for a successful sprint. There were some tasks that were easier to do with 
a partner and some that only required a single team member. The partner tasks generally went well for bouncing ideas off of another person, but could be 
difficult when two people were actually working on that same task at the same time (ex: homepage design) just because there was sometimes a slight disconnect.
Going forward we learned that when working on any tasks involving partners or the whole team, communication should be a priority to prevent redundant code 
(or other work) and allow for efficient implementation of ideas.

b. What did go well? Why?
Collaboratively coding the website design was pretty smooth as there were no major errors we encountered when implementing HTML and CSS. Everyone was also 
briefed on best practices when it comes to pulling changes from the GitHub repository, so there were minimal conflicts. Communication-wise, everyone proactively
addressed their minor blockers before they escalated into bigger issues. On top of that, if someone finished their tasks earlier than another team member, 
they were very quick to help someone else in need. Additionally, sprint meetings were well confined to a 15-minute window, and our meetings stayed on topic, 
making them efficient. Lastly, the goals were realistic as the team did not overcommit. Our sprint backlog was scoped well, and we weren’t overwhelmed with 
tasks beyond our capabilities and available time. 

c. What didn’t go well? Why not?
When writing code, especially with a team, we found that our code became somewhat clunky as new designs and features were added. This required us to make 
changes after realizing different code for different segments of the sprint were incompatible. An example of this would be two people adding css classes for 
different areas of the website, such as the homepage and navbar, that share sections with the same class, such as h1, h2, and h3. One person would make a 
change without realizing their css change impacted another area of the website. This led to a lot of retracing steps and having to make small changes later 
on as the team didn’t write code with future additions to the code in mind. Going forward future additions to the project will be considered and discussed 
by the whole team to prevent more clunky code from being added. We want new code to be seamlessly integrated with the code we already have.

d. How can you make things better next time?
As we approach the later phases of the project and get more heavily into coding, we want to ensure communication is strong and that code being added will 
still work well with new features as they get added. To do this we want to briefly discuss the full scope of the project and consider all future tasks each 
time our team has a scrum meeting. By mentioning each future task, even those in the backlog, team members will be well aware of what still needs to be added. 
By knowing what tasks are still incomplete, we all can code and design features with all future tasks in mind, which encourages each team member to write 
code that will be compatible with additions later on. We want new code to flow well with what is already written so discussion of the full project scope 
during each meeting will be important. Discussing the full project during each meeting also reminds members of who is responsible for which tasks and leads 
to more communication about how tasks will be completed. This prevents team members from stepping on each other’s foot and clearly defines responsibilities.

e. Are you satisfied with what you already completed?
As it stands, yes. We have a clear vision of what we want the end product to look like, and we’ve built a strong foundation through our core pages and 
nav bar. This has made it easier to build and connect different components of the site. While we have not encountered any major issues so far, we 
anticipate that challenges will arise as we continue implementing more advanced features, so we’ve remained mindful. Overall, we‘re satisfied with our 
current progress..

f. Which group was invited? What are your observations/notes? Everybody was present?
Group with Steven Aquirre, Nathan Wang, Chase Needelman, Harrison Reichert were present during the meeting. Their observations were as follows:
-Time management for meetings were good since meetings were less than 15 minutes
-Some team members contributed to conversations frequently while others were more silent. This may indicate engagement gaps or unclear role expectations. 
-Blockers were well handled as blockers were assigned a clear owner or follow up action
-Team morale was overall very strong as everyone had a positive tone throughout and are very willing to collaborate. 
